{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584473","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584473"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:47:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:47:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14584"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14584"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.02,0.97,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7277"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92614"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7277","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7277"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14584"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75954"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"688"},{"type":"tags","id":"1109"},{"type":"tags","id":"1307"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3576"},{"type":"tags","id":"4848"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17772"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30617"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31737"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92614","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/92614"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of increasing fatigue and unintentional weight gain of 5 kg. She reports feeling cold all the time, constipation, dry skin, and difficulty performing her usual daily activities. Her medical history includes hypertension and osteoarthritis. Her medications include amlodipine and paracetamol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears tired. Her pulse rate is 56/min, blood pressure 145/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. She has dry, coarse skin and delayed relaxation of ankle reflexes. Her thyroid gland is not palpable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Depression","Polymyalgia rheumatica","Primary hypothyroidism","Chronic fatigue syndrome","Iron deficiency anaemia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of hypothyroidism including fatigue, weight gain, cold intolerance, constipation, and dry skin. The physical examination findings of bradycardia, delayed ankle reflexes, and characteristic skin changes strongly support this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPrimary hypothyroidism\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents in older women with an insidious onset of symptoms. The combination of systemic symptoms with characteristic physical findings makes this the most likely diagnosis. Confirmation would require thyroid function tests showing elevated thyroid stimulating hormone (TSH) and low thyroxine (T4).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDepression\u003C/strong\u003E can present with fatigue and changes in weight, but would not explain the physical findings of bradycardia, delayed reflexes, and skin changes. However, depression can co-exist with hypothyroidism and may improve with thyroid replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic fatigue syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E is a diagnosis of exclusion and typically affects younger individuals. While fatigue is prominent, it would not account for the objective physical findings present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIron deficiency anaemia\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fatigue but would not explain the weight gain, cold intolerance, or characteristic physical findings. Additionally, anaemia typically causes tachycardia rather than bradycardia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPolymyalgia rheumatica\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with proximal muscle pain and morning stiffness, particularly in the shoulders and hips. While it can cause fatigue, it would not explain the other systemic symptoms and physical findings present in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe diagnosis of primary hypothyroidism is particularly important in older adults as symptoms may be attributed to normal aging or other conditions. Treatment with levothyroxine should be initiated gradually in older patients with careful monitoring of response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary hypothyroidism commonly presents with non-specific symptoms including fatigue, cold intolerance, and weight gain.","Physical examination findings of hypothyroidism include dry skin, bradycardia, and delayed relaxation of deep tendon reflexes.","Thyroid function tests are required to confirm the diagnosis of hypothyroidism, with elevated TSH and low T4 being diagnostic of primary hypothyroidism."],"references":["Valeria Calsolaro, Filippo Niccolai, Giuseppe Pasqualetti, Sara Tognini, Silvia Magno, Tommaso Riccioni, Marina Bottari, Nadia Caraccio, Fabio Monzani, Hypothyroidism in the Elderly: Who Should Be Treated and How?, Journal of the Endocrine Society, Volume 3, Issue 1, January 2019, Pages 146\u2013158, https://doi.org/10.1210/js.2018-00207 Available online at ; https://academic.oup.com/jes/article/3/1/146/5185175","So M, MacIsaac RJ, Grossmann M. Hypothyroidism. Aust Fam Physician. 2012 Aug;41(8):556-62. PMID: 23145394. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2012/august/hypothyroidism"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75954"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14584"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"75954","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/75954"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-18T15:23:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-18T15:24:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7277"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"92614"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/688"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name